title: For Sale:  mosin sniper package
postcontent: I have a 1943 Izhevsk Mosin Nagant sniper rifle, with matching numbered 3.5X PU scope. This is an original, not a century or arsenal rebuild. I have worked the harmonics down as far as I can, as well as worked the trigger a bit. It’s all original, just shoots really well. At 200 meters, surplus ammo is almost going thru the same ragged hole. I’m also including 50 rounds of new manufacture 185 grain ammo, and a translated Soviet Mosin Nagant sniper manual. This is the original manual issued to Soviet troops, just translated into English, not the U.S. Army manual created for U.S. troops. I can also include the original cleaning gear, cleaning rod, bayonet, sling, etc. to answer a few questions that have risen, the import was thru Century, the serial number was electro penciled (stamping was rare as the impact of the hammer and stamp could severely damage the optic), and all serial numbers match (receiver, stock, furniture, bolt, and scope mount). The serial number on the scope mount matches, but is in Latin letters, not Cyrillic, indicating it was built for the Ukrainian territory (remember, Ukraine used to be a soviet satellite state), and was certified as a soviet built sniper rifle by the Ukrainian government. I also, have no problem meeting, and allowing anyone to test fire the rifle, I understand it can be an investment, and I respect that. I used to do ww2 reenacting, and am having to resign my commission as a German Officer due to family obligations that take precedence. I am asking $800, but am open to non-insulting offers. Also, if you are an expert and would like to place your input, please contact me directly, and we can discuss whatever opinionated discrepancies you have. I am open to trades, especially for colt .45 1873 styled revolvers (soft spot), or under folding AKs. But please, don’t hesitate to make an offer! Thanks for checking it out, guys!

title: For Sale:  mauser
postcontent: I have an original WW2 Mauser sniper rifle. This does not include the single claw scope mount, and ZF-39 scope. There aren’t any import marks, either, indicating the rifle came into the country prior to 1968. The mounting holes are soft soldered plugged, which is what Germany had to do to “de-mil” a certain number of sniper rifles, after the war. This one is dated 1917, Danzig, and is Gew. 98. This rifle was cut down to a K98 sometime in WW2, and fitted to a CZ24 stock, and mounted with the ZF-39 single claw scope mount. This rifle is in great condition, and shoots wonderfully with good ammo. I’m getting out of ww2 reenacting, so I have no need for this any longer. This rifle is valued at around $650, I am asking $450, but I am open to trading for pretty much anything. So please, let me know what you have, OR make an offer (non-insulting, please).

title: For Sale:  Mossberg .30-06 Patriot Classic Walnut 22 inch Fluted Free Floating Barrel LBA Trigger & Weaver Mounts 4x4 type Exc Factory Demo 27861
postcontent: Seller Stock #: LG27861U Photos are representative, but buyer will receive a virtually identical rifle from the same shipment. Dealers and organizations may take any extras we have on hand at the same per-rifle price and with no additional shipping charges. Mossberg’s 4x4 rifles entered the field in 2007, after the company’s 40 year hiatus from high powered rifle manufacturing. Mossberg got it right, and here is the 4x4’s offspring, the Mossberg Patriot with American Walnut Stock chambered in the venerable .30-06 Springfield caliber. Manufacturer and warrantor is O.F. Mossberg & Sons of New Haven, CT, and Eagle Pass, TX. Type is bolt action high powered rifle with detachable magazine and 75 degree bolt throw. Construction is steel barrel, bolt, and receiver with polymer trigger housing, and removable internal polymer magazine. Chambering is .30-06 Springfield, with 4 shot magazine, so 4+1 total capacity. Barrel is 22 inch fluted, 1:10 right hand six groove button rifling; completely free floating, with counter bored or recessed muzzle crown. Outside barrel diameter is .620 at the muzzle and .730 at the forend tip and end of the flutes. Metal finish is non glare matte blue, with matching bolt face, handle, and gas deflecting cowl; and with spiral fluted matte finish steel bolt. This rifle comes furnished with mounted Weaver Scope Bases, #51 front and #36 rear, that measure 4 1/4 inches between their closest slots; screw spread is 4 5/8 inches. Safety is very quiet, mounted on the right side behind the bolt handle. Stock is classic satin finish American Walnut, with Monte Carlo and lateral stippled panels on the forend and pistol grip areas. Sling swivel studs are QD blue steel. Length of pull is 14 inches from the LBA Lightning Bolt Action trigger face to the end of the 1 inch decelerator type recoil pad. Weight empty is 6 pounds 14 ounces, with center of gravity 1 inch back of the bolt lugs. Trigger is factory LBA type, set on its 3 pound vicinity off the line setting, with negligible felt creep. This Patriot comes to us from Mossberg’s distribution system, where it likely served light duty as a showgirl for Mossberg’s sales team or with their publicity writers. It has the letter U stamped near its serial number. Surface detractions are minimal, principally faint contact marking on the stock and barrel. We rate it as Excellent, 90 percent vicinity by our estimate. Photos, at any rate, ought to suffice for our distinguished shoppers to judge finish grade for themselves. Bore, chamber, and mechanism are all bright and clean. If this rifle was ever fired, it was no more than 50 to 100 times. Fewer than 1 in 5 of its mates showed any green copper on our cleaning patches.
